default&#xa0;defaultCosts arising from the involvement of defaultTdefaulthird defaultPdefaultarty defaultIdefaultntervenersdefault&#xa0;
defaultThe government asks whether third parties who choose to intervene in judicial review claims
default can
default be responsible in principle for their own legal costs of doing so, such that they should not, ordinarily, be able to claim those costs from either the claimant or the defendant? 
default&#xa0;
defaultWe do not 
defaultconsider 
defaultthat a
defaultn NGO
default third party intervener should be 
defaultliable 
defaultfor 
defaulttheir own legal costs. We are concerned that the proposals relat
defaulting
default to third party interveners would have a detrimental impact on the role of NGOs and other important actors in the judicial review process. This is because making a
defaultn NGO
default third-party interven
defaulter liable for their own costs not only impacts negatively on the quality of the decision b
defaulty
default dissuading parties who may add substantive and significant arguments from intervening, but would also have a disproportionate effect on the ability of NGOs and char
defaultities to engage in the judicial review process, insulating the executiv
defaulte further from proper scrutiny and accounta
defaultbility in the exercise of power and demonstrating human rights compliance.
default&#xa0;
defaultThird party interventions can be extremely beneficial to the quali
defaultty of the decision making process in the 
defaultapplication
default. They may be able to bring additional expertise and arguments, particularly if they are an interest group that represents a particular group 
defaultwithin 
defaultsociety or 
defaultan 
defaultissue. The rules on costs might therefore
default discourage those who could bring something significant to the case due to their inability to bear the financial burden, particularly if they are an NGO with 
defaultrestricted 
defaultfinancial resources. This would consequently 
defaultlimit
default the ability of NGOs to engage in the
default judicial review process in general as the costs would prove a practical hindrance. This would furthermore affect the effectiveness of the judicial review process by limiting those who can engage in it to the financially stable and resourceful. Such a poli
defaultcy would again misunderstand the role of judicial review as a tool for the public to 
defaultchallenge the decision making function of 
defaultexecutive power
defaults
default by dictating the process along the lines of costs rather than the importance of 
defaultthe public interest/human rights
default issues in play.
default&#xa0;defaultFrom a practical perspective, the quality of the decision making process may be hindered if certain arguments or opinions are excluded. It may lead to an increase in subsequent costs because of the need for further litigation if important
default points are not raised or clarified in the original case due to a costs barrier. There is no real evidence to support the assertion that third party interveners greatly increase the costs in the first place, and their participation at the outset may lead t
defaulto a more efficient and thorough consideration of 
defaultthe 
defaultissues in the 
defaultapplication
default. 
default&#xa0;defaultThe intervention of a third party 
defaultNGO 
defaultmay bring an important 
defaultperspective to 
defaultthe 
defaultapplication 
defaultthat would not have otherwise been considered. The benefits that they can bring mean they should not 
defaultbe responsible for any additional costs that may be incurred. Furthermore, any intervention is at the discretion of the court who are in the best position 
defaultto restrict the involvement if it may not add anyt
defaulthing of value to the process. 
defaultA key consideration in deciding whether to apply to make a third party intervention in a judicial review is whether the intervention will add value to the application
default, and thus
default appropriate safeguards are already in place.
